properties.Summary:

Timing: Now through this afternoon. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 7:01 p.m. ADT, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing pea to dime size hail and heavy rain. Maximum rainfall rates 25 to 35 mm per hour. Locations: Goose Bay and Upper Lake Melville. Time span: this evening. Remarks: Satellite imagery indicates severe thunderstorms have developed producing intense downpours and small hail over the next couple hours. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Conditions will be favourable for the development of funnel clouds today. Hazard: Funnel clouds. In rare cases, these may develop into a landspout tornado. Source: A possible landspout tornado was reported near Almonte at 3:00pm local time. Timing: More funnel clouds and possible landspouts are possible through early this evening. ### These types of funnel clouds are generated by weak rotation under rapidly growing clouds or weak thunderstorms. This weak rotation is normally not a danger near the ground. However, there is a chance that this rotation could intensify and become a weak landspout tornado. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, at times heavy, is expected. Total rainfall: generally 35 to 45 mm with as much as 75 mm locally. Locations: Western and Mid Coast Labrador. Time span: tonight until mid day Monday. Remarks: Showers will change to rain, at times heavy, on Sunday with localized downpours possible. The rain is expected to ease Sunday night in Western Labrador and mid day Monday along the coast. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
